title: For Sale/Trade:  Martini Cadet in .219 Improved
postcontent: I have available for purchase something of an oddity.  I inherited this rifle and I recieved very little information about it before the former owner's death, so while this information is correct to the best of my knowledge I will admit it is outside my expertise.This is a Martini Cadet, produced in Austraila per reciever marks, and chambered in .219 Zipper or possibly Ackley Improved.  The former owner remakred that it was a 'PO Ackley Barrel' but he was old and suffering from dementia at the time.  The stock appears to be made of cherry wood and features a two tone stain as well as brass inlay and butt plate.  There is an additional decoration on the bottom of the pistol grip's flare: a rear of a .219 cartridge.  The optic has no markings and while it needs a thorough cleaning by a professional it appears intact and the reticle is quite crisp.  There are no visible markings on the optic's body and my eye is not keen enough to guess the magnification with any certainty.  I have further pictures available which better show the details.While the weapon does function and I can attest it is quite accurate, the embellishment, along with the scarcity of ammunition, does make this rifle perhaps better suited to decoration.  And what a decoration it is!  The leopard spot rosettes of the cherry are clearly visible and with the brass, all in very good condition, give this rifle the look of something from another time and place.  A young person today might describe it 'steampunk', something out of a Victorian England that never was.  In any case the original rifle was a military trainer eventually sold off by the Australian Government after they stopped using them in approx. 1955.  The barrel is a full replacement, which is clearly evident from the different metal conditions.  WHile I do not know when the barrel was replaced, I can verify the origin of the stockwork.  The deceased owner of the rifle constructed both the buttstock and the foregrip himself.These sorts of pieces not being my expertise, and the values acros the internet being quite inconsistant I do not know a proper value for the rifle, so all reasonable offers and trades will be entertained.While I do not know the exact date of manufacture, the original rifle from which this was built was produced at latest in 1949 and so it is very easily C&R.
